Medical emergencies, and how to act

First Aid (CPR and for Choking)

Cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR): An emergency treatment performed when a person’s heartbeat or breathing has stopped.

Pre-check:
Is the environment safe for the victim?
Is the victim aware, awake,  and alert of their environment? (Are they conscious?)
If not conscious, shake the victim’s  shoulder and loudly ask them, “Are you okay?”
If they don’t answer or do not give any sign, call 911.
Meanwhile, if anyone is available to provide help, have one of you find an AED if nearby.
The other must begin CPR, while connecting to the 911 emergency call, with speaker mode on.
If an AED is accessible, use it. The machine provides both visual and hearing instructions.
The machine contains sticky pads, placing them on the bare skin of the victim’s chest. Provide one shock if the machine indicates you to do so.
Start or Restart CPR.

If you are not trained in CPR: Follow steps 1-5, and repeat until medical help arrives.
If you are trained in CP, but unsure: Follow steps 1-5, and repeat until medical help arrives.
If you are trained and ready: Follow all steps.

CPR for an adult:
Lay the adult on a flat, hard surface.
Keep one hand directly over the other on the person’s lower half of the chest bone.
Your shoulders must be aligned with your hands, with elbows immovable.
Compression must be at least 2 inches of depth, and no more than 2.4 inches.
Perform 100-120 compressions per minute, with 30 times a set. Allow the chest to return to neutral position after each compression.
After each set, perform 2 rescue breaths if the person does not have a possible neck injury. 
If another person is available to assist, switch performing CPR every 2 minutes to avoid rescuer fatigue.
If not, open the airway of the adult victim by performing the head-tilt/chin-lift maneuver. 
Start by tilting their head back from its neutral position by placing your palm on their forehead. 
With your free hand, gently place your index and middle finger right on the bony part of the chin, with your thumb on top of the chin. 
Slowly tilt the chin upward and forward towards you.
Pinch the person’s nose and take a deep breath. Then, completely seal the person’s mouth with your mouth.
Make sure your breath lasts 1 second and monitor the chest rising, and allow air to exit before performing the next breath.
If the 1st  breath does not work because the chest does not rise, realign their head to open the airway neatly and seal your mouth properly and give the second breath. 
If the 2nd breath does not work even after realignment, there may be an object blocking the airway. 
Continue providing chest compressions even if the person does not breathe after the 2nd breath given.
Continue performing 100-120 chest compressions per minute,  and 2 rescue breaths after each set of 30 until paramedics arrive.

CPR for a child:

If you are by yourself and did not see the child lose awareness, perform CPR for 2 minutes. Then immediately dial 911 and get an AED if accessible in proximity.

If you are by yourself and see the child lose awareness, immediately dial 911. Acquire an AED if possible, then start CPR.

If you are not alone, have the other person get help immediately while you perform CPR.

Lay the child on a flat, hard surface.
Keep one hand directly over the other on the child’s lower half of the breastbone.
Your shoulders must be aligned with your hands, with elbows immovable.
Compression must be 2 inches of depth, and no more than 2.4 inches.
Perform 100-120 compressions per minute, with 30 times a set. Allow the chest to return to neutral position after each compression.
After each set, perform 2 rescue breaths if the child does not have a possible neck injury. 
If another person is available to assist, switch performing CPR every two minutes to avoid rescuer fatigue.
If not, open the airway of the child victim by performing the head-tilt/chin-lift maneuver. 
Start by tilting their head back from its neutral position by placing your palm on their forehead. 
With your free hand, gently place your index and middle finger right on the bony part of the chin, with your thumb on top of the chin. 
Slowly tilt the chin upward and forward towards you.
Pinch the child’s nose and take a deep breath. Then, completely seal the victims mouth with your mouth
Make sure your breath lasts 1 second and monitor the chest rising, and allow air to exit before performing the next breath. Also ensure you provide too many breaths or breaths with too much force for the child victim.
If the 1st  breath does not work because the chest does not rise, realign  the head to open the airway neatly and seal your mouth properly and give the second breath. 
If the 2nd breath does not work even after realignment, there may be an object blocking the airway.
If so, perform first aid for choking.
Continue performing 100-120 chest compressions per minute,  and 2 rescue breaths after each set of 30 until paramedics arrive.

CPR for a baby >= 4 weeks old:
Cardiac arrest in babies is most commonly due to a lack of oxygen, due to blocking of the airway. If so, provide first aid for choking. If not, turn to CPR.

First touch the baby without shaking them. If they don’t react, immediately call 911. 

Do NOT follow CPR procedures used for adults or children for babies up to 4 weeks old. Use such methods for babies under 1 years old.

Start CPR right away if you see the baby lose consciousness and use an AED if it is accessible. If another person is available to assist, have them get help and the AED. Stay with the baby and perform CPR.
Lay the baby on their back on a flat, hard surface. (Table or floor ideally)
Place two fingers in the center of the baby’s chest, just below the middle of their breastbone.
Gently perform 100-120 compressions a minute. 
Ensure each compression is about 1.5 inches of depth.
After the first set of 30 compressions, perform the head-tilt, chin-lift maneuver.
Start by tilting their head back gently from its neutral position by placing your palm on their forehead. 
With your free hand, gently place your index and middle finger right on the bony part of the chin, with your thumb on top of the chin. 
Slowly tilt the chin upward and forward towards you.
Completely cover the baby’s nose and mouth with your mouth.
Provide gentle puffs of air for each rescue breath, which last about one second.
If the chest does not rise after the first breath, provide a second breath.
If the chest of the baby still does not rise, perform chest compressions again. Repeat 2 rescue breaths every 30 chest compressions.
Continue performing CPR until the baby reacts or moves, or if the medical help arrives.

