When an object is stuck in the windpipe or throat, preventing air flow. Choking is a life-threatening scenario where it prevents flow of oxygen to the brain.

Children and adults choking:
Provide 5 back blows: situate yourself behind the adult choking. 
For a child, kneel down. 
Position your non-dominant arm over the person’s chest to provide support for their body. 
Gently bend them at the waist to face the ground. 
With your dominant hand, smack 5 times repeatedly with the heel of your hand between their shoulder blades.
If blows do not help dislodge the object, attempt the Heimlich maneuver.
Stand behind the person, and kneel down if it is a child.
Form a fist with one hand and position it right above the person’s navel.
Grab your formed fist with your other hand over the person and press it into the abdomen of the person.
Perform a rapid thrust upwards 5 times, like attempting to pick them up. In case for a child, apply less, but firm pressure.
Determine if the object is dislodged.
If not, repeat until the object comes out, or medical help arrives.
If the person is not reacting at all, perform CPR, and if trained, perform rescue breaths.

Babies < 1 year old choking:
Sit down and have the baby lay face down on your forearm, while supporting the baby’s chin and jaw. 
Allow the head to be positioned lower than the rest of the lower half.
Gently smack the baby’s back 5 times using the heel of your hand, while your fingers and face away from the baby’s head to avoid hitting.
If the baby still has not recovered the airway, turn the baby upwards and rest their head lower than the lower half.
Situate two fingers right beneath the nipple line. 
Compression depth should be around 1.5 inches.
Perform 5 chest thrusts. This mimics the Heimlich maneuver.
Allow the chest to return to neutral position after each compression.
Repeat smacks on the back and compressions to the chest if the baby still does not breathe, and await medical help.
Perform CPR if the airway is clear, but the baby still does not breathe.

If you are unable to wrap around the person, or the person is pregnant, then provide chest thrusts.
Position your hands at the lower portion of the breast bone, right above the joining the lowest ribs.
Perform a rapid thrust into the chest. This mimics the Heimlich maneuver.
Continue performing the rapid chest thrusts until the blockage is removed, or medical help arrives.

You are alone and choking:
Immediately dial 911.
Give yourself abdominal thrusts: form a fist.
Situate it just above the navel.
Grab your fist with your other hand.
Bend over a firm surface with a dull edge (chair or countertop works)
Push your fist in and up repeatedly.

Person is unconscious after choking:
Bring your ear to the person’s mouth and check signs of breathing, along with chest movement.
If the person is breathing, perform first aid for unconsciousness: lie the person on their back.
Roll them onto their side if no spinal injury is present.
Tuck the top leg so that it forms a right angle (L-shape)
Use the head-tilt/chin-lift maneuver.
Start by tilting their head back from its neutral position by placing your palm on their forehead. 
With your free hand, gently place your index and middle finger right on the bony part of the chin, with your thumb on top of the chin. 
Slowly tilt the chin upward and forward towards you.
If breathing stops or pulse ceases, immediately perform CPR.

