Medical emergency: Stroke

Severity: Critical, can lead to death.


Definition: Ischemic means restricting or reducing blood flow to a certain region of the body. An ischemic stroke happens when the blood flow is restricted to parts of the brain, causing brain cells to starve of oxygen and nutrients. The cells cease in minutes.

Hemorrhagic refers to a state of unbounded, extreme bleeding. A hemorrhagic stroke happens when a blood vessel lyses and causes bleeding in the brain. This results in increased blood pressure in the brain, which damages brain cells.

Triggers: Ischemic stroke - blocked artery. Hemorrhagic stroke - popping or leaking of a blood vessel in the brain. 

Symptoms: 
Headache
Paralysis or numbness in one side of the body, affecting leg, arm, or face.
Vision blurring or vision being blackened in either or both eyes. In some cases diplopia (seeing double) can occur.
Trouble understanding or speaking to others.
Having difficulty walking due to loss of coordination.
Drooling or unable to swallow.
Lack of reaction
Loss of memory
Change in mood
Rigidity of the neck


When to call 911: If any symptoms are seen, even at the slightest, perform the “B.E. F.A.S.T” checklist. If they have any of the conditions along with the symptoms, immediately call 911.

Balance: Check and confirm whether the person is dizzy or has a lack of coordination.
Eye: Determine if the person has difficulty seeing.
Face: Make the person smile. One side droops.
Arms: Make the person raise both arms. They are unable to lift either correctly, or one arm droops downwards or lack the power to raise their arm.
Speech: Make the person repeat a phrase. Speech slurring occurs, or is cannot speak normally.
Time: If any signs are seen, immediately call 911.

What to do meanwhile help arrives:
Mark down when symptoms have started if possible, as it can support the medical help administer specific treatments within a specific timeframe. 
When the person suffers a stroke, they tend to feel sleepy. Do not let them sleep.
If the person suffering a stroke loses awareness, make sure to check that they are breathing and have a pulse. If not, immediately begin CPR.

Transient ischemic attack (TIA) is known as a mini-stroke where a temporary drop in supplement of blood to the brain happens. This can last 5 minutes. These can show similar symptoms to stroke. Still call 911 if you experience a TIA, as it can potentially increase chances of contracting a stroke.

What to avoid: 

To take time and see if symptoms improve: can cause severe brain damage in minutes if treatment is not received.

To sleep while having a stroke: it offsets treatment administration.

Taking the person suffering a stroke or yourself to an emergency room: emergency medical hep immediately provides treatment upon arrival.

Do not take or provide drinks, foods, or any medications to you suffering or the person suffering the stroke: medications such as aspirin can have an adverse effect on stroke, and drinking or eating is to be avoided as strokes cause difficulty swallowing.

Citations: Mayo Clinic, Holy Cross Health, American Red Cross, CDC, Cleveland Clinic,
NIH 

