Medical emergency: Cardiac Arrest

Severity: Critical, can lead to death


Definition: Occurs when the normal electrical rhythm of the heart experiences a problem that causes the heart to malfunction or completely stop beating. When the heart cannot pump blood, one loses consciousness. Cardiac arrest becomes lethal in mere minutes. 

Triggers: Abnormal heart rhythms (arrhythmia), coronary artery disease (CAD), severe injury or excessive loss of blood, severe infections, structural changes to the heart, heart, blood vessel, or heart valve diseases, thick heart muscle, fainting are examples of what may cause cardiac arrest.

Symptoms: 
Abnormal breathing.
Dizziness.
Lack of breath.
Pain or feeling pressure in the chest.
Gasping.
Vomiting and/or Nausea.
Heart palpitations.
Unusual fatigue.
Pain in the stomach.
Symptoms of the flu.



