Medical emergency: Severe bleeding 
Severity: Critical


Definition: External bleeding occurs on the outside of a person’s body. It can be severe and life-threatening if the flow is gushing or continuous, and if the volume of the blood loss is equivalent to half of what a typical soda can contain. If such bleeding matches these conditions, the person is in life-threatening condition.

Triggers: Deep rooted wounds or large wounds that have hit arteries.

Symptoms: 
Volume of blood is about half a soda can (and relatively smaller for children or babies)
A sign of shock
Blood is gushing or flowing continuously.



When to call 911: If bleeding is flowing non-stop without control, is not clotted, and bleeding persists, immediately call 911.

What to do meanwhile help arrives:
If possible, wash your hands immediately.
Use latex gloves (ones in first aid kits) if possible.
Make sure no clothing or debris is covering the wound of the person.
Determine if there is more than one wound. 
Do not try to clean the wound, or remove deeply rooted or big items. 
Do not try to aggravate the wound.
Find clean clothes or aseptic gauzes.
Ensure the body part injured is laid on a flat, firm area.
Place it over the person’s wound and apply pressure with the palm of your hand.
If it is a deeply rooted object, or an injury in the eye, do not apply pressure.
If there is a possibility of a skull fracture, do not apply pressure.
Envelop the wound with a clean cloth, bandage with thickness, or tape.
Lay down the injured person on a rug, or ensure a blanket covers their body to keep them warm
If the person shows weakness, a quick pulse, or other signs of shock, place the feet higher than the rest of the body.
If the wound continues to bleed through the bandaging, use another clean cloth or an aseptic gauze to press onto the previous bandage. 
Continue applying pressure.
If you are trained, use a tourniquet on the injured limb. Tell medical help when it arrives about how long the tourniquet has been in place.
If you are trained, use wound packing if the bleeding occurs on the groin, back, neck, scalp, or shoulder.
If bleeding is stopped, ensure that blood circulation is still allowed past the injury.
Wrap another bandage over the previous dressing to ensure security.
Ensure again that blood circulation is still allowed past the injury.
If bleeding occurs again, do not apply anything. 
Keep the remaining dressings on the wound in place, and wait for medical help to arrive.

What to avoid: 

Removing paddings after bleeding has stopped: it will disrupt the blood clots forming that are held together from the pressure.

Not washing your hands after helping, though no blood is on your hands.





Citations: Mayo Clinic, Harvard Education, Medlineplus 

